verleden","Abt 1212":"circa 1212","Abt 1200":"circa 1200","1212":"1212","1200":"1200","1240":"1240","1140":"1140","1162":"1162","Abt 1160":"circa 1160","1183":"1183","1160":"1160","Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Pathhead, Midlothian, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Scotland":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1160–Abt 1212":"about 1160–about 1212","1160–1212":"1160–1212","1162–Female":"1162–Deceased","1200–1240":"1200–1240","1140–1183":"1140–1183","1140–Female":"1140–Deceased","Abt 1212":"about 1212","Abt 1200":"about 1200","1212":"1212","1200":"1200","1240":"1240","1140":"1140","1162":"1162","Abt 1160":"about 1160","1183":"1183","1160":"1160","Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Crichton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Creighton   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Creighton","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: habitational name from Crichton, near Edinburgh, first recorded <i>c.</i> 1128 in the form <i>Crectune</i>, in 1287 as <i>Crecton</i>, and in 1360 as <i>Creychtona</i>. The name is probably an early hybrid compound of Old Welsh <i>creic</i> ‘rock’ + Older Scots <i>tun</i> ‘farm, settlement’ (Old English <i>tūn</i>). In Ireland and Britain, this form of the name is now found chiefly in northern Ireland; the more usual Scottish forms are   Crichton   and   Crighton  .","Irish: sometimes used for Gaelic <b>Ó Creacháin</b> or <b>Ó Criocháin</b> (see   Crehan  ).","English: habitational name from Creighton in Staffordshire, named with Celtic <i>creig</i> ‘rock’ + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’."]}]},{"name":"Thurston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly East Anglia):","from the Anglo-Norman, Anglo-Scandinavian, and Middle English personal name <i>Thurstan</i>, <i>Thorsten</i> (Old Norse <i>Thórsteinn</i>, <i>Thorsten</i>, Anglicized as Old English <i>Thurstān</i>; see   Thorstensen  ).","habitational name from Thurston in Suffolk, so called from the genitive case of the Old Norse personal name <i>Thóri</i> (see   Thor  ) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Tustin","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of the Latin name <i>Augustinus</i> (  see  Augustine  ). Both forms were used selectively in various regions of England as late as the 17th century and they are found occasionally much later, but the present-day use of this form as a given name is normally a reintroduction from its survival as a surname. It is particularly popular in the United States."]},{"name":"Thruston","meanings":["English: metathesized form of   Thurston   1."]},{"name":"Thorstensen","meanings":["Norwegian and Danish: patronymic from the personal name <i>Thorsten</i>, a variant of <i>Thorstein</i>, Old Norse <i>Thórsteinn</i>, composed of the name of the god <i>Thórr</i> (see   Thor  ) + <i>steinn</i> ‘stone, rock’, hence meaning ‘altar of Thor’ or perhaps ‘hammer of Thor’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thurston Crichton was born about 1160, in Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, William Crichton, was 21 and his mother, Lady William Crichton, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Thurstone de Crichton. He died about 1212, at the age of 54."},"et":{"Abt 1160–Abt 1212":"umbes 1160–umbes 1212","1160–1212":"1160–1212","1162–Female":"1162–Surnud","1200–1240":"1200–1240","1140–1183":"1140–1183","1140–Female":"1140–Surnud","Abt 1212":"umbes 1212","Abt 1200":"umbes 1200","1212":"1212","1200":"1200","1240":"1240","1140":"1140","1162":"1162","Abt 1160":"umbes 1160","1183":"1183","1160":"1160","Pathhead, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Pathhead, Midlothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1160–Abt 1212":"noin 1160–noin 1212","1160–1212":"1160–1212","1162